    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3462906092" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3462906092" />
    <a title="JimZ" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/99765491-jimz"><img alt="JimZ" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1575257175p2/99765491.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3462906092?book_show_action=true">Jul 26, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="JimZ" class="user" itemprop="url" name="JimZ" href="/user/show/99765491-jimz">JimZ</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781590172254" href="/book/show/398352.The_Enchanted_April">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3462906092" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1840240659934549730">Another 5 star-er! 😊 I’m so happy! Nothing like a great read to make me happy.<br/><br/>This is the second book I have read by Elizabeth von Arnim and I gave ‘Vera” 5 stars too.<br/><br/>In “Vera” von Arnim had a plot line which at least to me was sinister and worrying and dark but at the same time she had me at time laughing out loud. How do you explain that?! I think it is called tragi-comedy. Anyway, in The Enchanted April (published in 1921, re-issue I had was by New York Review of Books, 2007) it is all lighte</span>
  <span id="freeText1840240659934549730" style="display:none">Another 5 star-er! 😊 I’m so happy! Nothing like a great read to make me happy.<br /><br />This is the second book I have read by Elizabeth von Arnim and I gave ‘Vera” 5 stars too.<br /><br />In “Vera” von Arnim had a plot line which at least to me was sinister and worrying and dark but at the same time she had me at time laughing out loud. How do you explain that?! I think it is called tragi-comedy. Anyway, in The Enchanted April (published in 1921, re-issue I had was by New York Review of Books, 2007) it is all lighter fare. I was wondering what was going to happen as I approached the end, but it wasn’t with a feeling of dread, as it was in ‘Vera’. Well, that’s not exactly true. I will leave that enigmatic statement there for people to ask “what the hell is he saying?” You just have to read the book.<br /><br />What I found interesting about this book is that it reminded me of ‘Cold Comfort Farm’ (1932) by Stella Gibbons. In this book there is Mrs. Fisher with her “stick”…I guess it’s apparently her cane and she says she can’t do certain things because of her “stick”…it’s just weird….similar to the elderly Ada Doom in Cold Comfort Farm when she says that as a girl “I saw something nasty in the woodshed” and this is the reason why she hasn’t left her room in many a year. And then there is Lotty Wilkins in this novel…and just her air of positivity after she leaves the confines of her house in London and goes to Portofino Italy to a medieval castle for a one month vacation — she reminds me of Flora Poste, the central protagonist in Cold Comfort Farm who has such a positive, can-do attitude in the story. And in that novel Gibbon had me laughing out loud at times and so that too happened in this novel by von Arnim. Rare for a book even that is touted as witty or as humorous to make to me chuckle or laugh out loud but now von Arnim has done it in the two books I have read by her. <br /><br />The main protagonists are 4 women…three are in their late 20s and one if 65 but acts as if she’s 95. She’s Mrs. Fisher and her character is a real doozy…for me to describe her anymore than that would take some of the fun out of reading the novel. Well, let me say she reminds me of a female Ebenezer Scrooge. Then there are two married women who have problems with their marriages…Dotty Wilkins and Rose Arbuthnot. Reasons for their unhappiness are different. Then there is a superficially beautiful-in-physical-appearance-and-demeanor Lady Caroline (nickname ‘Scrap’). She is an interesting character but one thing that had me laughing was that even when she was pissed off and would say some rude and curt thing to one of the three other women or to the hired help in the castle that the physical makeup of her voice box and tongue and vocal pitch would make whatever rude thing she would say as if she didn’t really mean it and was being nice to the person she was directing her curtness/rudeness to. <br /><br />An example is called for here…Lady Caroline is interacting with the cook, Costanza:<br />…Lady Caroline scowled at the cook. The scowl, as usual, was transformed on the way into what appeared to be an intent and beautiful gravity, and Costanza threw up her hands and took the saints aloud to witness that here was the very picture of the Mother of God. Lady Caroline asked her crossly what she wanted, and Costanza’s head went on one side with delight at the sheer music of her voice…”She is not my mother,” repudiated Lady Caroline angrily; and her anger sounded like the regretful wail of a melodious orphan. <br />Poor Lady Caroline could say nothing wrong even when she did! Too beautiful for her own good…<br /><br />And stuck-up Mrs. Fisher…annoyed at how Mrs. Wilkins began some of her sentences: …”You see,” Mrs. Wilkins said—a silly trick that, with which she mostly began her sentences; Mrs. Fisher each time wished to say, “Pardon me—I do not see, I hear”—but why trouble?... It reminded me a childhood friend of mine…I would say “Hey!” to draw his attention to me. And he would say “I am not a commodity.” Like WTF??!!!<br /><br />I took notes while reading this novel—and I read it in one sitting because I could not put it down—and most of the notes were along the lines of:<br />Too funny!! LOL moment.<br />Too funny…<br />So funny….<br /><br />The plot line is rather simple….four unhappy women each for different reasons end up wanting to take a one month vacation and end up in an idyllic medieval castle in an idyllic port town of Italy. It is their interactions and their internal musings to themselves that make for delicious reading. And then later on in the book three male characters end up at the castle. Mr. Wilkins, Mr. Arbuthnot, and the owner of the castle, Mr. Briggs. Mr. Wilkins is a hoot. <br /><br />What I found interesting is that Elizabeth von Arnim wrote ‘Vera’ first, in 1921, and then wrote this book right after that, ‘The Enchanted April,’ in 1922. “Vera” was supposedly based on her failed and disastrous marriage to the older brother of Bertrand Russell, Frank Russell. I find it interesting that her wit was infused in “Vera” even though it was dark and then once she had that out of her system she wrote an entirely different and more uplifting book, The Enchanted April.<br /><br />Reviews:<br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/jul/22/enchanted-april-von-arnim-review">https://www.theguardian.com/books/201...</a> (I agree with reviewer that as the book winds down it became for me a 4 star book but that was late in the game for me so that for me the book in its entirety merited 5 stars) <br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.npr.org/2012/05/21/149549005/elizabeth-von-arnim-s-enchanted-april">https://www.npr.org/2012/05/21/149549...</a> (From NPR series, You Must Read This)<br /><br />There is a nice Introduction by Catherine Schine in the NYRB re-issue. Her most recent novel is The Grammarians (2019).<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1840240659934549730" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


